merican attorney, politician, former federal prosecutor and former [[United States Marine Corps|Marine]] serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Pennsylvania's 18th congressional district]] since 2018. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he won a [[Pennsylvania's 18th congressional district special election, 2018|special election]] that attracted national attention, held on March 13, 2018 in which he defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Rick Saccone]] by 755 votes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/01/04/republican-super-pacs-surge-into-pennsylvania-special-election/|title=Republican super PACs surge into Pennsylvania special election|work=The Washington Post|date=January 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Vox>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/3/14/17109448/pennsylvania-special-election-conor-lamb-defeats-rick-saccone|title=It\u2019s official: Democrat Conor Lamb wins Pennsylvania special election in major upset |last=Nilsen |first=Ella|date=March 14, 2018|work=Vox|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"general election results\">{{cite web |title=Pennsylvania Elections-Office Results|url=http://electionreturns.pa.gov/|publisher=Pennsylvania Department of State |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2018/01/05/special-election-18th-district-conor-lamb-rick-saccone/stories/201801050142|title=So it begins? National groups investing in Pa-18 special election |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=January 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/23/republicans-brace-for-competitive-pennsylvania-house-race-316206|title=Democratic wave: Republicans are bracing for a potentially competitive special election in a usually reliable part of Pennsylvania |newspaper=Politico|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> After Pennsylvania's congressional map was redrawn by [[Pennsylvania's congressional districts#2012 redistricting and gerrymandering challenge|court order]], Lamb filed to run for a full term in the neighboring [[Pennsylvania's 17th congressional district|17th congressional district]] in the 2018 general election.\n\nLamb was a federal prosecutor in the U.S. Attorney's office in [[Pittsburgh]], where he led prosecutions of cases involving opioid-related deaths, violent crimes, and gun trafficking.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/12/27/first-special-election-of-2018-is-in-trump-country-and-democrats-are-drooling/|title=First special election of 2018 is in Trump country \u2014 and Democrats are drooling|work=Salon|date=December 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Jenkins>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5193497/conor-lamb-pennsylvania-18th-saccone/ |title=Meet Conor Lamb, the Democrat Who Could Pull Off an Upset in Pennsylvania's Special Election|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=March 12, 2018|accessdate=March 13, 2018|last=Jenkins|first=Nash}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education==\nLamb was born in [[Washington, D.C.]] on June 27, 1984, to Thomas F. Lamb, Jr. and Katie Lamb. He grew up in [[Mt. Lebanon Township, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Mt. Lebanon]], a suburb in the south hills of Pittsburgh, and for a brief period in Connecticut. The Lamb family has been active in Pittsburgh-area politics for many years. Conor's grandfather, [[Thomas F. Lamb]], was the Democratic Majority Leader in the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] and later Secretary of Legislative Affairs under Governor [[Robert P. Casey]].<ref name=Tackett>{{cite web|last=Tackett|first=Michael|last2=Martin|first2=Jonathan|title=Who Is Conor Lamb, Winner in a Special House Race in Pennsylvania?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/14/us/politics/who-is-conor-lamb.html|website=The New York Times |accessdate=March 15, 2018|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ove|first1=Torsten|title=Obituary: Thomas F. Lamb / Masterful state political figure known as firm and fair|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/obituaries/2015/05/10/Obituary-Thomas-F-Lamb-Masterful-state-political-figure-known-as-firm-and-fair/stories/201505100143|accessdate=October 6, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=May 10, 2015}}</ref> Conor's uncle Michael Lamb is the Controller of the City of [[Pittsburgh]], and was previously the [[Prothonotary]] of [[Allegheny County, Pennsylvania]].\n\nA [[Irish Catholics|Catholic of Irish descent]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2018/02/18/conor-lamb-pennsylvania-special-election-profile-217018 |title=Is Conor Lamb the Next Big Democratic Upset? |work=[[Politico]] |date=February 18, 2018 |first=Jim |last=Saksa}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/12/2018-special-election-first-ripple-in-a-democratic-wave.html|title=Pennsylvania Special Election Could Be the First Ripple in a Democratic Wave|work=New York Magazine|date=December 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/meet-conor-lamb-democrat-nab-seat-trump-country/story?id=53685989 Meet Conor Lamb, the Democrat looking to nab a seat in Trump country], ''[[ABC News]]'', Adam Kelsey & Erica King, March 13, 2018. Retrieved March 14, 2018.</ref> Lamb attended St. Bernard School in Pittsburgh, and graduated from [[Central Catholic High School (Pittsburgh)|Central Catholic High School]] in 2002. He graduated from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 2006 with a B.A. degree in political science, and earned a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from the [[University of Pennsylvania Law School]] in 2009.\n\n== Military service ==\n\nAfter law school, Lamb completed the Marine Corps' [[Officer Candidates School (United States Marine Corps)|Officer Candidates School]] before being commissioned as a [[United States Marine Corps Judge Advocate Division|Judge Advocate General officer]].  As his first duty assignment, he was stationed at a Marine base on [[Okinawa Island]], where he prosecuted cases of rape and sexual assault. Following completion of his active duty service in 2013, Lamb continued his military obligation through service in the [[United States Marine Corps Reserve]] as a [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]]. He would later be promoted to [[Major (United States)|major]]. In a high-profile case in 2017, he prosecuted and convicted a Marine officer who had lied under oath and to ''[[The Washington Post]]'' about a sexual misconduct case.<ref name=Jackson>{{cite web | url=https://www.factcheck.org/2018/02/nrccs-weak-case/ | title=NRCC\u2019s Weak Case | work=[[Factcheck.org]] | date=February 28, 2018 | accessdate=March 16, 2018 | last=Jackson | first=Brooks}}</ref><ref name=Marimow>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/marine-pleads-guilty-to-lying-in-sexual-misconduct-case-says-he-crossed-the-line/2017/04/13/d3fd9cf6-2064-11e7-a0a7-8b2a45e3dc84_story.html | title=\u2018Ready to pay\u2019: Marine taken in shackles after pleading guilty to lying in sexual misconduct case | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=April 13, 2017 | accessdate=March 16, 2018 | last=Marimow | first=Ann | last2=Cox | first2=John}}</ref>\n\n== Assistant U.S. Attorney ==\nFrom 2013 to 2014, Lamb clerked for [[Joseph Frank Bianco]], a federal judge in the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York]]. Following his clerkship, in October 2014 Lamb was appointed an [[Assistant United States Attorney]] in the [[United States Department of Justice]]'s Pittsburgh office, serving under then-U.S. Attorney for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Pennsylvania|Western District of Pennsylvania]] [[David J. Hickton]]. Lamb has been heavily involved in efforts to combat the opioid epidemic in Western Pennsylvania, and has led aggressive prosecutions involving opioid-related deaths, other violent crimes and drug and gun trafficking.\n\nDuring Lamb's election campaign for the 2018 special election for [[Pennsylvania's 18th congressional district]], Republicans accused Lamb of having a \"weak record\" as a prosecutor, referencing particular cases in support of this claim.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2018/02/nrccs-weak-case/|title=NRCC's Weak Case - FactCheck.org|date=February 28, 2018|work=FactCheck.org|access-date=March 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> [[FactCheck.org]] examined the Republicans' claims, calling them \"vague\" and \"misleading,\" and found little evidence to support them.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Notable cases ===\n==== \"Uptown Crew\" gang prosecution ====\nIn 2015, Lamb won convictions against three men who were among 34 members of a heroin gang indicted in 2013 after a wiretap investigation by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives|ATF]], the state attorney general's office and local police. Thomas Hopes, described as the \"CEO\" of the violent heroin-distribution operation, was sentenced to 24 years in federal prison, and brothers Keith and Gregory Harris were sentenced to 20 years and 121 months in prison, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ove|first1=Torsten|title=Heroin boss gets 24 years in N.J.-to-Homestead federal drug case|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/local/south/2016/03/11/Heroin-boss-gets-24-years-in-NJ-to-Homestead-federal-drug-case-homestead-pennsylvania/stories/201603110230|accessdate=October 6, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brothers Sentenced for Participating in a Violent Drug Conspiracy|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-wdpa/pr/brothers-sentenced-participating-violent-drug-conspiracy|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=October 6, 2017|date=February 29, 2016}}</ref> Lamb also helped win convictions against two New Jersey-based men, Aldwin Vega and Santino Drew, who were identified as two of the biggest suppliers of heroin to the Pittsburgh area. Vega was convicted at trial in September 2017 for trafficking a kilogram or more of heroin, and has not yet been sentenced. Drew was found guilty of conspiracy to distribute heroin and possession with the intent to distribute heroin, and was sentenced to 20 years in federal prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Federal Jury Finds New Jersey Man Guilty Of Supplying Heroin To Pittsburgh-based Drug Ring|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-wdpa/pr/federal-jury-finds-new-jersey-man-guilty-supplying-heroin-pittsburgh-based-drug-ring|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=October 6, 2017|date=May 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Pittsburgh-to-New York gunrunning prosecution ====\nIn 2016, Lamb won convictions against two Pittsburgh residents, Brandon Goode and Mychael Scott, who acted as \"straw buyers,\" purchasing firearms for a gun trafficker to help funnel hundreds of illegal weapons into New York City. Goode and Scott were sentenced to 65 and 60 months in prison, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ove|first1=Torsten|title=Two Pittsburgh straw buyers convicted in gunrunning network sentenced|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/local/region/2016/08/02/Two-Pittsburgh-straw-buyers-convicted-in-gunrunning-network-sentenced/stories/201608020154|accessdate=October 6, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> Lamb also secured a conviction against the main gun trafficker, Michael Bassier, who was sentenced to 10 years in federal prison.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mandak|first1=Joe|title=Man gets 10 years for Pennsylvania-to-New York gun running|url=http://www.mcall.com/news/local/police/mc-man-gets-10-years-for-pennsylvania-to-new-york-gun-running-20161213-story.html|accessdate=October 6, 2017|work=The Morning Call |location=Allentown, Pennsylvania |agency=Associated Press|date=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Andre Saunders ====\nIn 2016, Lamb secured a conviction against Andre Saunders, a drug dealer from [[Fayette County, Pennsylvania]], who imported hundreds of kilograms of cocaine and heroin from the West Coast into the Uniontown area and West Virginia and supplied heroin and cocaine to multiple dealers in the Uniontown area. Saunders was convicted of conspiracy to distribute heroin and cocaine and sentenced to 10 years in prison, and was ordered to forfeit his BMW, five luxury watches and a necklace, $325,120 in cash, his Uniontown home, the proceeds of the sale of a second Uniontown home, a 9-mm pistol, and a money judgment of $100,000.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lord|first1=Rich|title=Fayette County heroin dealer sentenced|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/overdosed/2016/05/23/OVERDOSED-special-report/stories/201605230152|accessdate=October 6, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=May 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Dorian Cottrell ====\nIn 2016, Lamb won a conviction against Dorian Cottrell, a heroin dealer who shot a man during a drug transaction at the Cambridge Square apartments in Monroeville, PA. Cottrell was sentenced to 15 years in federal prison and was ordered to forfeit his BMW, $27,000 in cash and 10 firearms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ove|first1=Torsten|title=Monroeville heroin dealer gets 15 years in federal prison|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/local/east/2016/03/17/Dubbed-a-shooter-young-heroin-dealer-gets-15-years-in-federal-prison/stories/201603170182|accessdate=October 6, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n\n=== Elections ===\n==== 2018 special election ====\n{{Main|Pennsylvania's 18th congressional district special election, 2018}} \n[[File:Conor Lamb (40636199252).jpg|thumb|Lamb at a March 2018 rally]]\nOn October 5, 2017, the ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'' reported that Lamb was considering running for Congress in a special election for Pennsylvania's 18th congressional district. The vacancy was created when Representative [[Tim Murphy (American politician)|Tim Murphy]] (R) resigned amid revelations that he had had an extramarital affair and urged his mistress to terminate an unexpected pregnancy, despite his long record as a vocal opponent of abortion.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Potter|first1=Chris|title=Tim Murphy's departure brings many would-be replacements, as well as a ray of hope for Democrats|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-nation/2017/10/05/Tim-Murphy-s-departure-brings-multiple-would-be-replacements-as-well-as-a-ray-of-hope-for-Democrats/stories/201710050240|accessdate=October 6, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Murphy had run unopposed by a major candidate for his prior two elections, 2016 and 2014.\n\nLamb was selected as the Democratic nominee at a convention in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.padems.com/2017/11/conor-lamb-wins-first-ever-congressional-democratic-convention/|title=Conor Lamb Wins First-Ever Congressional Democratic Convention|date=November 19, 2017|publisher=Pennsylvania Democratic Party|access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref> He faced Republican State Representative [[Rick Saccone]]. The special election attracted national attention. National Republican sources spent more than $8 million on television advertising, twice as much as the Democrats, and Republican stars including [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]], his two children [[Donald Trump Jr.|Donald Jr.]] and [[Ivanka Trump|Ivanka]], as well as [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] came to the state to campaign for Saccone.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/12/pennsylvania-special-election-lamb-saccone-454728|title=Republicans wage 11th-hour blitz in Pa. special election|last1=Schneider|first1=Elena|last2=Isenstadt|first2=Alex|date=March 12, 2018|work=Politico|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nLamb's campaign website lists his top priorities as the heroin crisis, jobs and infrastructure, affordable health care, protecting Medicare and Social Security, reforming the student loan system, unions, and modern energy development.<ref>{{cite web|title=Priorities - Conor Lamb |url=https://conorlamb.com/priorities/|website=Conor Lamb|publisher=Conor Lamb for Congress |accessdate=February 15, 2018}}</ref> On gun control, Lamb has called for a stronger system of background checks but no new restrictions. On tariffs, Lamb supports President Trump's steel and aluminum tariffs. On health care, Lamb criticized the Republican attempt to repeal [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Obamacare]] and called for bipartisan efforts to stabilize its markets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/13/politics/pennsylvania-18th-lamb-saccone-on-the-issues/index.html|title=Where Conor Lamb, Rick Saccone stand on the issues|last=Bradner|first=Eric|date=March 13, 2018|work=CNN|access-date=March 14, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of election night on March 13, 2018, Lamb led by 641 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/13/us/politics/lamb-saccone-pennsylvania-election.html|title=Pennsylvania House Race, in a District Trump Won by 20 Points, Is Too Close to Call|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=March 13, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 14, 2018|last2=Burns|first2=Alexander|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cohn|first1=Nate|title=Pennsylvania Special Election Results: 18th Congressional District|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/03/13/us/elections/results-pennsylvania-house-special-election.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=March 14, 2018|date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> When all absentee ballots were counted, Lamb led by 627 votes,<ref name=\"Vox\" /> with a few provisional and military ballots yet to be counted.<ref name=\"recount\">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/14/recount-pennsylvania-special-election-2018-413822|title=Republicans prepare for recount in Pennsylvania special election|last=Schneider|first=Elena|date=March 14, 2018|work=Politico|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Lamb claimed victory on Tuesday night. Early on Wednesday morning, citing the large net pickup of absentee votes for Lamb, NBC News called the race for Lamb.<ref name=\"NBCCall\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/pennsylvania-special-election-conor-lamb-rick-saccone-n856411|title=Democrat Conor Lamb apparent winner in Pennsylvania upset, deals blow to Trump|author1=Alex Seitz-Wald|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> On Wednesday afternoon, ''The New York Times'' followed suit after concluding that Lamb's lead, while narrow, appeared \"insurmountable.\"<ref name=\"NYTcall\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/14/us/politics/democrats-republicans-pennsylvania-special-election.html|title=Conor Lamb Wins Pennsylvania House Seat, Giving Democrats a Map for Trump Country|author1=Alexander Burns|author2=Jonathan Martin|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> However, most news outlets did not declare a result, noting the closeness of the vote (just 0.2% separates the candidates) and the likelihood of a recount.<ref name=\"recount\" /> However, when it became apparent that Saccone would not pick up enough votes to overtake Lamb, he called Lamb to concede the race on March 21.<ref name=\"concession\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/21/politics/lamb-saccone-concession/index.html|title=Republican Rick Saccone concedes 8 days after Pennsylvania special election|last=Bradner|first=Eric|date=March 22, 2018|work=CNN|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nLamb's lead came primarily on the strength of winning the Allegheny County portion of the district by almost 15,400 votes. He lost the rest of the district by 14,700 votes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/election/2018/pennsylvania-house-special-election |title=Pennsylvania's House special election 2018 |work=[[CNN]]}}</ref> \n\nAfter Lamb's apparent win in the special election, Republicans claimed that he won because \"he ran as a conservative\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-falsely-brags-to-donors-that-conor-lamb-liked-the-gop-tax-reform|title=Trump Falsely Brags to Donors That Conor Lamb Liked the GOP Tax Reform|last=Resnick|first=Gideon|date=March 15, 2018|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=March 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/3/14/17119662/paul-ryan-conor-lamb-pennsylvania-spin|title=Paul Ryan says Conor Lamb, who ran against the GOP tax plan, ran \"as a conservative\"|work=Vox|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> This was a distinct shift from the campaign, during which Republicans said Lamb \"Walks The Liberal Party Line\" and chastised him for opposing the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Republican 2017 tax reform bill]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Lamb ran against the law, describing it as a \u201cgiveaway\u201d to large corporations and a \u201cbetrayal\u201d of middle-class Americans.<ref name=\":0\" /> Trump asserted that Lamb had said he \"liked Trump\", but there is no evidence of Lamb ever doing so.<ref name=\":0\" /> Conor Lamb was certified as the winner on April 2, 2018, winning by 755 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-nation/2018/04/02/Conor-Lamb-Allegheny-County-election-results-certified-winner-congressional-seat/stories/201804020086|title=Finally official: Conor Lamb certified winner of congressional seat|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=April 2, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He was sworn in by [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Paul Ryan]] on April 12, 2018,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theincline.com/2018/04/12/conor-lamb-is-finally-officially-the-u-s-representative-for-pennsylvanias-18th-district/|title=Conor Lamb is finally, officially the U.S. Representative for Pennsylvania's 18th District|work=The Incline|access-date=April 13, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and became the first Democrat to represent this district since 2003, when it was numbered as the 20th District.[[File:LAMB LogoMed.png|thumb|Conor Lamb 2018 campaign logo]]\n\n==== 2018 general election ====\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2018#District 17}}\n\nAfter the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]] threw out the state's original congressional map and replaced it with a court-drawn map, the old 18th was reconfigured as the [[Pennsylvania's 14th congressional district|14th District]] and made even more Republican on paper. Meanwhile, Lamb's home in Mt. Lebanon was drawn into the [[Pennsylvania's 17th congressional district|17th District]]. That district had previously been the [[Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district|12th]], represented by three-term Republican [[Keith Rothfus]]. While the old 12th was one of Trump's strongest districts in Pennsylvania in 2016, Trump would have only barely carried the new 17th. It also voted for Democrats downballot. This led to speculation that Lamb would run in the new 17th, regardless of the special election results.<ref name=\"cbq\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/02/19/upshot/pennsylvania-new-house-districts-gerrymandering.html |newspaper=The New York Times |department=The Upshot |title=The New Pennsylvania House Districts Are In. We Review the Mapmakers' Choices. |date=February 19, 2018 |access-date=February 20, 2018 |first1=Nate |last1=Cohn |first2=Matthew |last2=Bloch |first3=Kevin |last3=Quealy }}</ref> On March 14, [[Beaver County, Pennsylvania|Beaver County]] Democratic Party chairman Stephen Dupree told [[ABC News]] that Lamb submitted a written request for county Democrats to endorse his bid for the 17th in the November 2018 general election; Beaver County is entirely within the new 17th.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/conor-lamb-rick-saccone-run-november-congressional-districts/story?id=53782730|title=Conor Lamb, Rick Saccone to run again in November in new and different congressional districts|author1=Emily Goodin|author2=John Verhovek|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> On March 16, Lamb announced on his [[Twitter]] account that he was in the process of gathering petitions for a run in the 17th.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=ConorLambPA|number=974687309256904704|title=Stop by our Carnegie office this weekend to sign & pick up petitions & help get Congressman-elect Conor Lamb on the ballot in 2018!|date=March 16, 2018|last=Lamb|first=Conor|authorlink=Conor Lamb}}</ref> On March 20, he formally submitted petitions for a full term in the 17th.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/03/20/conor-lamb-won-pennsylvanias-18th-district-tuesday-he-filed-states-17th-district/443460002/|title=Conor Lamb won Pennsylvania's 18th district. Tuesday he filed in the state's 17th District|author1=Eliza Collins|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref> On May 15, he faced an uncontested primary and will face [[Keith Rothfus]] in November.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania Primary Results, US House: Guy Reschenthaler tops Rick Saccone in 14th District; Mike Doyle wins easily|url=http://www.wtae.com/article/pennsylvania-primary-election-results-us-house/20685459|website=WTAE|language=en|date=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology|'''Committee on Science, Space, and Technology''']]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Veterans' Affairs|'''Committee on Veterans' Affairs''']]\n**[[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs|Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs]]\n**[[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n**[[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Technology Modernization|Subcommittee on Technology Modernization]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://veterans.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2210|title=Chairman Roe, Ranking Member Walz Name Lawmakers to New Subcommittee on Technology Modernization|last1=Roe|first1=Phil|date=July 12, 2018|website=House Committee on Veterans Affairs|publisher=Tiffany Haverly|language=en}}</ref> (Ranking Member)\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n\n*\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! colspan=\"5\" {{party shading/Democratic}} | Democratic nominating convention, 2018<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.padems.com/2017/11/conor-lamb-wins-first-ever-congressional-democratic-convention/|title=Conor Lamb Wins First-Ever Congressional Democratic Convention - Pennsylvania Democratic Party|date=November 19, 2017|publisher=[[Pennsylvania Democratic Party]]|access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=PADems |number=932321173173669888 |date=November 19, 2017 |title=Results from round one of voting: Lamb: 225, Cerilli: 153, Iovino: 90, Crossey: 47, Brock: 21, Solomon: 18, Seewald: 0. Lamb, Cerilli, and Iovino advance to round two. |archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=PADems |number=932327705818910721 |date=November 19, 2017 |title=Results from round two: 545 total votes cast this round. Iovino: 74, Cerilli: 152, Lamb: 319. |access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=PADems |number=932327787003830274 |date=November 19, 2017 |title=.@ConorLambPA wins! |access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#eee; text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 12em\" |Candidate\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width: 5em\" |First ballot\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width: 5em\" |Pct.\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\